1
00:00:00,680 --> 00:00:05,759
The Andrews pitchfork indicator, commonly
referred to as 'median lines' is one of the

2
00:00:05,759 --> 00:00:08,430
most versatile trading tools available.

3
00:00:08,430 --> 00:00:14,380
Andrews’ pitchfork consists of a median
line at the center and two parallel equidistant

4
00:00:14,380 --> 00:00:20,820
trend lines, where the outside trend lines
represent areas of support and resistance.

5
00:00:20,820 --> 00:00:25,660
Traders often look for buying or selling opportunities
as the price approaches the ends of these

6
00:00:25,660 --> 00:00:26,660
channels.

7
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:32,970
In this chart, for example, the price remains
largely within the bounds of the indicator

8
00:00:32,970 --> 00:00:37,140
with the exception of several short false
breakouts.

9
00:00:37,140 --> 00:00:39,820
The Andrews pitchfork works in any time frame.

10
00:00:39,820 --> 00:00:44,390
This, of course, can range from tick charts
to monthly.

11
00:00:44,390 --> 00:00:49,450
This allows the indicator to work well for
day trading and long-term investing.

12
00:00:49,450 --> 00:00:52,610
The indicator can also work on any security.

13
00:00:52,610 --> 00:00:58,250
So, whether you like to trade forex, futures
or stocks, you can incorporate this versatile

14
00:00:58,250 --> 00:01:01,270
tool in your analysis.

15
00:01:01,270 --> 00:01:06,479
The Andrews pitchfork indicator is created
by selecting three points on a chart:

16
00:01:06,479 --> 00:01:10,060
A beginning point that represents the start
of a trend.

17
00:01:10,060 --> 00:01:14,440
(We’ll call this point A)
A reaction high coming after the beginning

18
00:01:14,440 --> 00:01:15,440
point.

19
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:16,840
(Point B)

20
00:01:16,840 --> 00:01:19,950
A reaction low coming after the beginning
point.

21
00:01:19,950 --> 00:01:23,610
(Point C)
The selection of these points is somewhat

22
00:01:23,610 --> 00:01:28,690
subjective, but it’s a good idea to experiment
with different reaction highs and lows to

23
00:01:28,690 --> 00:01:31,009
find what works best.

24
00:01:31,009 --> 00:01:36,040
In some cases, you may want to plot multiple
Andrews’ pitchforks on the same chart to

25
00:01:36,040 --> 00:01:41,299
provide an indication of where support or
resistance may be strongest.

26
00:01:41,299 --> 00:01:46,040
You may also look at different timeframes
to determine long-term and short-term support

27
00:01:46,040 --> 00:01:49,170
and resistance levels for a given security.

28
00:01:49,170 --> 00:01:54,520
You need to identify the right points in your
analysis, because the success or failure of

29
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:59,840
interpreting signals depends largely on how
you plot the median lines.

30
00:01:59,840 --> 00:02:05,259
In most cases, drawing the median lines is
rather subjective, but with practice, you

31
00:02:05,259 --> 00:02:07,869
can develop the confidence required.

32
00:02:07,869 --> 00:02:13,629
A rather simple method is after pivot points
are identified, tweak the median lines to

33
00:02:13,629 --> 00:02:17,230
encapsulate price action with the greatest
level of accuracy.

34
00:02:17,230 --> 00:02:23,180
If you master how to use Andrews pitchfork
, you will have a competitive advantage ahead

35
00:02:23,180 --> 00:02:28,849
of the market, because you will know the dynamic
support and resistance levels in advance.

36
00:02:28,849 --> 00:02:35,000
Now, not all three trend lines that make the
Andrews pitchfork react the same.

37
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:38,419
They offer different levels of support and
resistance.

38
00:02:38,419 --> 00:02:41,849
The Andrews pitchfork indicator has three
lines.

39
00:02:41,849 --> 00:02:44,579
Each line starts from the pivot.

40
00:02:44,579 --> 00:02:49,799
We have ml (median line), the uml (upper median
line) and lml (lower median line).

41
00:02:49,799 --> 00:02:52,700
But, they don’t have the same importance.

42
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:56,730
By far, the most important one is the median
line.

43
00:02:56,730 --> 00:03:00,180
It has one big advantage: it attracts price.

44
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:03,590
As such, it acts like a magnet.

45
00:03:03,590 --> 00:03:07,469
Because of that, traders use it to adjust
their trading strategies.

46
00:03:07,469 --> 00:03:11,010
There are many ways to use this powerful trading
tool.

47
00:03:11,010 --> 00:03:13,769
Some traders use it as a single indicator.

48
00:03:13,769 --> 00:03:16,989
Others integrate the pitchfork with other
trading tools.

49
00:03:16,989 --> 00:03:22,799
In any case, there’s not one Andrews pitchfork
strategy that works all the time.

50
00:03:22,799 --> 00:03:27,239
The classical way to use this trading tool
is to look after support and resistance levels.

51
00:03:27,239 --> 00:03:33,930
As you know, when we analyze a price chart,
we can find classic and dynamic support/resistance

52
00:03:33,930 --> 00:03:35,099
levels.

53
00:03:35,099 --> 00:03:39,329
With this tool however, the dynamic ones are
more valuable.

54
00:03:39,329 --> 00:03:44,290
The bigger the time frame, the more powerful
the reaction from the levels will be.

55
00:03:44,290 --> 00:03:50,280
The idea is to integrate the dynamic support/resistance
rules with Andrews pitchfork power.

56
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:53,249
Pay attention at this example.

57
00:03:53,249 --> 00:03:59,639
The three pivots (a, b, c) give the angle
and the shape of Andrews pitchfork.

58
00:03:59,639 --> 00:04:04,529
The resulting lines act as future dynamic
support/resistance levels.

59
00:04:04,529 --> 00:04:09,370
As always, once a level gets broken, resistance
turns into support.

60
00:04:09,370 --> 00:04:11,930
And, the other way around.

61
00:04:11,930 --> 00:04:16,380
Judging by the current prices, the outlook
looks bullish.

62
00:04:16,380 --> 00:04:19,150
The key here is the medial line.

63
00:04:19,150 --> 00:04:24,050
Many traders misinterpret how to use Andrews
pitchfork’s ml.

64
00:04:24,050 --> 00:04:27,840
While it attracts the price, it doesn’t
offer any support.

65
00:04:27,840 --> 00:04:29,020
Nor resistance.

66
00:04:29,020 --> 00:04:34,319
Just the fact that it pierces it is enough
for a strong trend.

67
00:04:34,319 --> 00:04:38,090
Strong trends see the ml guiding the price
action.

68
00:04:38,090 --> 00:04:42,409
Eventually, the price will pierce it multiple
times.

69
00:04:42,409 --> 00:04:47,780
As a rule of thumb, while the price stays
within Andrews pitchfork lines, the trend

70
00:04:47,780 --> 00:04:49,349
will keep going.

71
00:04:49,349 --> 00:04:54,020
The fact that it pierces the ml multiple times
shows strength.

72
00:04:54,020 --> 00:04:58,389
Hence, you must not use this as support or
resistance.

73
00:04:58,389 --> 00:05:00,910
Here is another example, to make it very clear.

74
00:05:00,910 --> 00:05:04,949
We identified, the A point as the start of
the move.

75
00:05:04,949 --> 00:05:09,110
Next, the B is the end of the first drop.

76
00:05:09,110 --> 00:05:13,259
Finally, the C point is the end of the first
swing higher.

77
00:05:13,259 --> 00:05:14,389
The resulting Andrews pitchfork shows a very
strong downtrend.

78
00:05:14,389 --> 00:05:20,169
Even if the price gets above the upper ml,
the bearishness is overwhelming.

79
00:05:20,169 --> 00:05:25,010
On top of it, the ml attracts the price on
a constant basis.

80
00:05:25,010 --> 00:05:32,219
Furthermore, the upper ml and lower ml act
as strong support and resistance levels.

81
00:05:32,219 --> 00:05:36,690
Using Andrews pitchfork this way gives dynamic
support and resistance levels.

82
00:05:36,690 --> 00:05:41,039
But, this is valid only for the upper median
line UML and lower median line LML.

83
00:05:41,039 --> 00:05:46,969
For the median line ML, multiple piercings
simply show how strong the trend is.

84
00:05:46,969 --> 00:05:49,240
In this case, very strong.

85
00:05:49,240 --> 00:05:53,530
However, how do we know when the trend ends?

86
00:05:53,530 --> 00:05:56,570
When should bulls consider a bottom is in
place?

87
00:05:56,570 --> 00:06:00,430
The way to answer these 2 questions is to
use the Schiff line.

88
00:06:00,430 --> 00:06:03,039
Few traders know about the Schiff line’s
existence.

89
00:06:03,039 --> 00:06:08,310
This is a line that connects the a point and
c point.

90
00:06:08,310 --> 00:06:12,650
As such, traders know in advance where the
Schiff line is.

91
00:06:12,650 --> 00:06:18,219
In strong trends, the price has a strong tendency
to move away from it.

92
00:06:18,219 --> 00:06:23,789
As a rule of thumb, a bearish trend keeps
going as long as the price stays below the

93
00:06:23,789 --> 00:06:24,789
Schiff line.

94
00:06:24,789 --> 00:06:28,120
Of course, the opposite happens in a bullish
trend.

95
00:06:28,120 --> 00:06:31,669
Here’s the Schiff line on the previous chart.

96
00:06:31,669 --> 00:06:34,090
It shows when the bearish trend ended.

97
00:06:34,090 --> 00:06:38,909
In fact, it shows when bears should not consider
selling anymore.

98
00:06:38,909 --> 00:06:45,169
Because the Schiff line gets broken, it means
bulls will step in on any future pullbacks.

99
00:06:45,169 --> 00:06:51,529
Now, based on the median lines and the Schiff
line, the two most common strategies falling

100
00:06:51,529 --> 00:06:58,910
under the s/r umbrella include:
Buying/selling the bounce.

101
00:06:58,910 --> 00:07:05,379
Traders may buy when prices hit the bottom
of a channel, but only in an uptrend and sell

102
00:07:05,379 --> 00:07:10,110
when prices hit the top of the channel only
in a downtrend.

103
00:07:10,110 --> 00:07:14,889
In these cases, it’s important to wait for
confirmation that the price is responding

104
00:07:14,889 --> 00:07:16,889
to these levels.

105
00:07:16,889 --> 00:07:29,629
Here are several examples of buying the bounce.

106
00:07:29,629 --> 00:07:43,770
The second strategy involves, buying/selling
the break.

107
00:07:43,770 --> 00:07:48,979
Traders may buy when the price produces a
breakout from the top of a channel or sell

108
00:07:48,979 --> 00:07:52,389
when price breaks from the bottom of the channel.

109
00:07:52,389 --> 00:07:57,199
In these cases, it’s important to look for
a clean break to avoid false breakouts.

110
00:07:57,199 --> 00:08:03,189
My favorite way to use the Andrews pitchfork
is to look for divergences between the pitchfork

111
00:08:03,189 --> 00:08:05,110
and RSI.

112
00:08:05,110 --> 00:08:09,040
If you followed by channel, you know that
i consider the divergence one of the most

113
00:08:09,040 --> 00:08:11,680
powerful leading signals you could get.

114
00:08:11,680 --> 00:08:17,169
So I look to buy or sell the breakout from
the pitchfork, only when i see a divergence

115
00:08:17,169 --> 00:08:18,840
on the RSI.

116
00:08:18,840 --> 00:08:22,050
This is powerful stuff, and let me demonstrate
it.

117
00:08:22,050 --> 00:08:27,479
In this first example, you can see how the
bearish divergence was formed with price making

118
00:08:27,479 --> 00:08:32,210
a higher high while the relative strength
index was seen making a lower high.

119
00:08:32,210 --> 00:08:37,130
Following this, price eventually broke down
through the lower median line following the

120
00:08:37,130 --> 00:08:38,490
price failure.

121
00:08:38,490 --> 00:08:45,510
In the next example, you can see that while
prices posted a lower low, but the RSI signaled

122
00:08:45,510 --> 00:08:50,660
a higher high, which indicated a bullish divergence
in price.

123
00:08:50,660 --> 00:08:56,260
This leading signal suggested that price would
be reversing upward shortly.

124
00:08:56,260 --> 00:09:00,940
Following the breakout from the upper median
line, we can see that a long position resulted

125
00:09:00,940 --> 00:09:04,279
in a profit as price continued to push higher.

126
00:09:04,279 --> 00:09:08,620
I strongly encourage you to search for this
pattern on your charts.

127
00:09:08,620 --> 00:09:23,829
Here are other trades based on RSI divergences
and Andrew’s pitchfork breakouts.

128
00:09:23,829 --> 00:09:38,050
Andrews’ pitchfork is a great price action
indicator to use when determining areas of

129
00:09:38,050 --> 00:09:39,170
support and resistance.

130
00:09:39,170 --> 00:09:45,230
While it’s not perfect in every scenario,
the indicator provides a good indication of

131
00:09:45,230 --> 00:09:47,829
where prices may be headed.

132
00:09:47,829 --> 00:09:52,980
The downside is that picking the main three
points is a largely subjective process that

133
00:09:52,980 --> 00:09:54,400
requires experience to master.

134
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:55,400
The Andrews pitchfork as a trading tool has
a bit of mystery for retail traders.

135
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:56,400
While everyone knows to use it in a trend,
few know how to master it.

136
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:57,400
The key stays with the main 3 pivot points.

137
00:09:57,400 --> 00:09:58,400
If you learn to draw them correctly, the Andrews
pitchfork indicator works like a charm.

138
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:01,190
Here’s one last important tip: a great way
to use this tool is to perform a top/down

139
00:10:01,190 --> 00:10:05,389
analysis (meaning to study all timeframes).

140
00:10:05,389 --> 00:10:11,930
Start from the biggest one (monthly) and continue
with the weekly chart, daily and the four-hour

141
00:10:11,930 --> 00:10:12,930
one.

142
00:10:12,930 --> 00:10:18,029
A multi-timeframe analysis with Andrew’s
pitchforks will result in a better understanding

143
00:10:18,029 --> 00:10:19,260
of market conditions.

144
